<P>On the birth of my lovely boy, new concerns occupied my <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">nd, and new plea&s;ures opened on my heart, that led me to forget the hard&s;hips of a &s;eparation from the parents that gave me being&mdash;Mr. Stanford's attention to me &s;eemed to <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> on this event. He devi&s;ed pretexts for vi&s;iting home, and found ways of accompli&s;hing more of his bu&s;i|ne&s;s at our own little retreat&mdash;in &s;hort, we both now &s;eemed perfectly reconciled to our lot&mdash;we pardoned, and began to re|member no more the &s;everities we had felt. In our devotions, in books, our own conver&s;ation, dome&s;tic endearments, and the &s;ociety of a few friends, who occa|&s;ionally
