<P>It happened one day, that mr. Stan|ford was called to go a few miles from the city, to receive a &s;um of money that was due to the per&s;on whom he &s;erved. He hired a hor&s;e in the morning, and promi&s;ed to be back ear|ly in the afternoon&mdash;he was detained &s;ometime longer than he expected&mdash;it was late in the afternoon before he &s;et off&mdash;on his return home, as he ap|proached the city, he was &s;topped by two ruffians, who demanded his mon|ey.&mdash;He did not choo&s;e tamely to &s;ub|mit to their demands, but with his whip attempted re&s;i&s;tance.&mdash;The vil|lains, armed with bludgeons, attack|ed him with violence&mdash;knocked him down&mdash;&s;tript him of his money and a great part of his clothes&mdash;and left him for dead in the highway. Some benevolent travellers, who happened &s;hortly after to be coming towards London, had him taken up and con|veyed to the next public hou&s;e&mdash;re|&s;toratives were applied; and through the influence of medical aid, he was
<PB N="100" REF="030546_0094_0FE7C4C36A202E00">
