<P>The propo&s;ition of leaving my friends and my country, I mu&s;t own, at fir&s;t &s;tartled me much: and in the apprehen&s;ion of the moment, I &s;ug|ge&s;ted that I did not think I could com|ply with her benevolent reque&s;t; but at her solicitation, <HI>I</HI> agreed to con&s;ider the matter &s;eriou&s;ly. But as to being pre&s;ent at her marriage, <HI>I</HI> told her whatever plea&s;ure <HI>I</HI> might once have taken in a circum&s;tance of that kind, at pre&s;ent it would recal too ma|ny painful &s;cenes of memory, and at once give me di&s;tre&s;s, and ren|der me a damp to <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> enjoyment of others. A few days after this, when my friend had returned to her father's, <HI>I</HI> pondered &s;eriou&s;ly on the pro&s;pect <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">he had opened to my view. On the one hand, <HI>I</HI> pictured to my&s;elf the pain of parting forever from many <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> <HI>I</HI> loved, al|though &s;ome <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">d treated me unkind|ly&mdash;the dangers of the ocean&mdash;the uncertainty of my fate when <HI>I</HI> reach|ed
